{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588286"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:05:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:05:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15125"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15125"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.09,0.27,0.09,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7813"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50120"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21400"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64686"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) is a common condition affecting the upper gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about GORD is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It only occurs in people with hiatus hernias","It does not cause oesophageal strictures","Only the distal 5 cm of the oesophagus is affected","Spontaneous resolution occurs within five years","The refluxate contains acid and bile"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGORD is characterised by the reflux of gastric contents into the oesophagus. \u003Cstrong\u003EBoth acid and bile\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in the pathophysiology of GORD, not just acid alone. The condition can affect anyone, not just those with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehiatus hernias\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGORD can lead to various complications including \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal strictures\u003C/strong\u003E through chronic inflammation and scarring. The condition can affect \u003Cstrong\u003Eany part of the oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E that comes into contact with the refluxate, not just the distal portion. Without treatment, GORD typically becomes chronic and \u003Cstrong\u003Edoes not resolve spontaneously\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic GORD can lead to Barrett oesophagus, where normal squamous epithelium is replaced by intestinal metaplasia (Image). This change represents an adaptation to chronic injury but also increases the risk of adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) involves reflux of both acid and bile","Chronic GORD can lead to Barrett oesophagus, characterized by intestinal metaplasia","GORD can create a self-perpetuating cycle through lower oesophageal sphincter damage"],"references":["Dent J, El-Serag HB, Wallander MA, Johansson S. Epidemiology of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease: a systematic review. Gut. 2005 May;54(5):710-7. doi: 10.1136/gut.2004.051821. PMID: 15831922; PMCID: PMC1774487","Tack J, Pandolfino JE. Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease. Gastroenterology. 2018 Jan;154(2):277-288. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2017.09.047. Epub 2017 Oct 14. PMID: 29037470","Herregods TV, Bredenoord AJ, Smout AJ. Pathophysiology of gastroesophageal reflux disease: new understanding in a new era. Neurogastroenterol Motil. 2015 Sep;27(9):1202-13. doi: 10.1111/nmo.12611. Epub 2015 Jun 5. PMID: 26053301","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50120"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15125"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21231"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21231"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/voCEpdHVtm80FeNvQhTu0nWAjzwZv6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/voCEpdHVtm80FeNvQhTu0nWAjzwZv6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":510,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50120"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T14:50:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T14:51:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7813"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64686"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":